<Rating>3<//Rating><time>1535842400932</time><Review>This is tucked in the corner of a very traditional Chinese plaza next to the Hilton. The restaurant serves Northern Chinese-style congee. I ordered the Lamb Congee, Chinese donut & potstickers. The congee is decent, loaded with lots of lamb, vegetables & is very hardy.... Good comfort food. The flavor is nice, kind of mild, you'll have to season to taste. There's a bean sauce at the table that is quite flavorful & compliments the congee nicely. This is the 2nd time ordering this Lamb Congee and both times i was quite satisfied. The potstickers though, were another story. They were small, smaller than the length of my pinky finger and deep fried completely to the point of complete loss if flavor. These potstickers were even worse than ones found at boba shops that barely cook anything. These potstickers were utterly DEPLORABLE and a shame to be even served at any authentic Chinese restaurant. The lamb congee however was pretty decent,  quite good with the bean sauce at the table and filled with good lamb slices. Just stay away from the potstickers.<//Review></record></dataset><record>

< Text>
I wanted to give it a 4.5 star JUST BECAUSE the price is overly expensive.

BUT!

Considered about me or other people can always review this place / look at the menu price / ask for the market price on the seafood before ordering and dining in

I'll give it a 5 star because the food quality and the taste is well deserved.

FRIENDLY REMINDER: PRICE CAN BE EXPENSIVE so think before you act.

We "looked up on yelp reviews and price" and decided to give it a try and check it out because the price of this place is pretty famous for expensive congee in the SGV area.

We order 2x dried scallop, prawn and clams congee ( $14.99 x 2 ) + a 2.5LB of crab ( market price is $25/LB ) + pea sprouts ( $10.99 ). It comes out to be around $107. So you see, price is considered expensive for chinese restuarant.

BUT!

The pea sprouts came first and it tasted decent - good i would say and its better than 90% of other places in the area so the price for this is alright.  The seafood congee is wonderful with alot of taste and alot of FRESH "seafood" in there. Congee price is double the ones outside but its worth it.  The Crab is also fresh and it had alot of meat but thats the most over price one.

I would totally recommend this place.  Other than the QUALITY AND TASTE OF IT, Not because i have the money or I'm rich but I know what I pay and I know what I want to try and check it out before I come.

THINK CAREFULLY BEFORE YOU COME BUT ONCE YOU DECIDE TO TRY THIS OR DINE IN AND ORDER THEN PLEASE DON'T COMPLAIN ABOUT THE PRICE. BE SMART.</Text>

Perhaps one of the best sauce and youtiao (kinda like an asian savory churro/donut), crispy and lightly sweet, I've had. The porridge (we got their signature seafood combo) is also delightful, they make it on the spot and the ingredients are fresh, full of flavor but no heavy lingering aftertaste. The fermented bean preserve on the side also go wonderfully with the porridge. Fast, clean service, would recommend.<//review>

<review>The hotel is conveniently located in Nob Hill close to most if not all attractions. the Cable car stop sits across the street of the hotel and the bus stops to Union Square, fisherman wharf are a block away. The staffs are friendly and helpful. My only issue was that the hotel cleaning schedule is not frequent enough. I stayed for 1 week and my room was cleaned only once. <gmapID>0x80858094a685e009:0xab09b07956096301<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>
< Text>
I liked my two night stay in this SF hotel. Historic, rebuilt in 1906 just after the big earthquake and resulting fires, or so we were told.

Shared bathrooms that were very clean, and I never encountered a closed door.

Well kept and actually quite charming in a real old timey sense. Staff was very polite and responsive to our wants and needs. These people care and try their best to satisfy. The noise from the cable cars and the bar next door didn't keep me awake. Trader Joe's and CVS right across the street.

It is getting better but is worst generally in the morning and at nights, and as such I was walking down the stairs the last day we were there (Thursday June 26, 2014) and because I nearly missed a step and tried to make up for it, a gentleman (and I am using this word VERY generously because I am an actual gentleman) said that I was too "inebriated" even though it was 9am and I was sober and willing to take a sobriety test, asking them for the police to come.

</record></dataset><record>
< rate>
5< /rate>
< Response>
None< /Response>
< Text>
Price:

The biggest room of the CCC is still quite cheap compared to other rates. Especially if you chose a weekly rate, you're at like 70/80 $ a day (tax included). Most rooms that are THAT central are much more expensive.

Getting around:

The California Line is right outside and is one of the cable car lines that has a high frequency. The Cable Car takes you down to Market (F line, tons of Buses) or to Powell (other Cable Car) to walk down to Union Square.

If you walk up a couple of blocks you can catch the buses 19, 47, 49 which take you to most connections or places.

If you arrive from the Airport DONT try to walk there. It's non stop uphill from the BART.

The place:

- Security is tight. RFID chip to enter and at 7 pm - 6 AM there's a security guard in the lobby. That is pretty nice, knowing that the Tenderloin is just a couple of blocks away
- The hotel offers no meals.
- 70$ security deposit is required
- They say Wifi is only available in the lobby but my room had full signal non stop. FREE OF CHARGE. However it got spotty around 9 pm.
- There are Laundromats in the lower level. You can also use the ones around you. There are at least 3 in walking vicinity
- WALGREENS, CVS, TRADER JOEs are less than 2 blocks away.
- The Fridge and Microwave worked perfectly
- House keeping only comes in once a week. However whenever I needed towels or stuff, I could just ask and I got them

The room:

I had a room in the Top floor facing away from the street and it was quiet and nice. I'd recommend to get a room in the 3rd or 4th floor facing away from the street. Windows aren't sound proof and the cable car can be loud.

- I got the biggest room WITH own toilet and shower and all of those things were really nice.
- Furniture was fine so were Fridge and Micro Wave.
- As stated I did have WIFI in my room which was pretty nice.
- The double room is only for singles or couples. Two buddies traveling might find it to be too cozy.
- The bed is crazy soft.
- The room had no separate heat. I visited in the summer time so that was no issue. Not sure about winter tho.
- The other guests are mostly tourists and a few commuter.

conclusion:
If you're looking for a cheap place in SF, that has the prices of a hostel but the amenities of a hotel, go to the CCC. It's central, cheap and well equipped for the price. Especially the top level floor rooms are very decent.
I removed one star because the carpet in the room had some stains in it and the towels could have been newer (they were washed but some of them had holes in them).< /Text>

<Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
(Translated by Google) Newly renovated hotel.
Very well located and easy to access.
Please note this is not a luxury hotel, but for $ 100 we were not disappointed.
Shared bathroom but cleaned 3 times a day so very clean.
A guard at the entrance who controls all arrivals and cameras in all the corridors.
Each room has a sink, fridge, microwave and desk.
We stayed there for 4 days.

Jose and Louis spent two days working with me on a wheel setup, pricing, and even so much as to meet with me and get my wheels on my car after hours. Jose and Louis go the extra mile to help their customers and although this is a business, they will not pressure you to buy anything. I felt as if Jose and Louis genuinely cared about me as a person rather than a sale. <Time>1554843628029</Time><rate>3</rate><Text>3 stars only because the guy who helped me was very nice. As a used car buyer, learn to ask questions and always have a mechanic look over the car you‚Äôre interested in.

After test driving the car - first thing the manager said to me was ‚Äúso how do you want to pay?‚Äù I said hold on hold on. I asked for the Carfax report - turns out the car had been in an accident. Which can be ok, but after I had a mechanic come to look at the repair job .. turns out the car was a disaster. It was not welded correctly, the battery moved all around out of place, other pieces were unstable/missing screws, and there was rust in the car.

Not to mention the price was a bit fishy. If it was in good shape, it would have been fine. But the car was truly a disaster, and they also claimed the DMV title transfer was ‚Äú$400‚Äù which in no way is true.

*When buying a used car here are the steps you need to take:

Inspect car for scrapes and dents on the outside

Inspect inside for rips and cleanliness/smell

Test drive car - first without AC or radio so you can hear if there are any unusual sounds

Ask for a Carfax report. See if the car has been in any accidents, and how many owners the car has had

Ask for the WALK AWAY price of the car. They always hit you with high tax and fees

< text>
When I walked in I was very warmly greeted by the host, a young man with a big smile and great attitude. He was excellent at communicating and my sister and I were seated in less than four minutes; however, it was all downhill from that point. FIRST, to the left of the front door the bar is located and I watched a server putting a straw in a drink and throwing the wrapper on the floor.

The service was incompetent and inadvertently forgot two separate request and refused to show up to the table with a pad and writing tools to take the order to help her retention, instead she spent the entire experience apologizing.

When our food arrived, my food was lukewarm and my Sister's fettucine was overcooked and lacked seasoning. My swordfish was undercooked, the vegetables were charred but raw, and the potato romano was almost cold. When we informed the server, she apologized again and had a new plate brought out 45 minutes into the experience and 15 minutes after my Sister's meal. Sad part was that I was celebrating my Sister's birthday.

Needless to say, it was a horrible experience the food is incredibly bland, the bar staff are unprofessional, and the chef does not care what comes out of the kitchen. Save your money and protect your memories that you attempt to create with your family.<//text>

While this restaurant looks amazing as it has a very casual feel to it which I love, I didn't have a good experience here. I ordered the seafood platter which was a huge letdown. For $19, there wasn't much seafood or fries in it, presentation sucked and it tasted kinda blahh. Our server was nice but he would ask us every 5-10 mins if we're okay or if we needed anything else like he wanted us to leave so he can get his tip already but the restaurant wasn't even packed. I would check out the other restaurants around the downtown Sta Barbara area.</text>

To start, no more free parking. Today, for my birthday I wanted a hamburger for lunch. For years I have been telling people the best burger in town was here. After looking at the menu and only seeing the enterprise burger I asked the waitress if they still had the regular burger that they used to have. What came to the table was a enterprise burger which has, bacon, mushrooms, onions, arugula and a fried egg, NOT what I ordered. So it was taken back and the next burger had absolutely nothing on it. Instead of taking it back the items were brought to me so I could put it together.  Wasn't able to finish the burger since I ordered it well done and it was med to rare!! Since I don't like sea food and the burger is NOT the best burger in town anymore, I will not be back again. <Name>D. Green</Name><Date>1534116139587< /Date><rate>2</rate>< Review>
To start, no more free parking. Today, for my birthday I wanted a hamburger for lunch. For years I have been telling people the best burger in town was here. After looking at the menu and only seeing the enterprise burger I asked the waitress if they still had the regular burger that they used to have. She said it wasn't on the menu but they still made it, so that is what I ordered. What came to the table was a enterprise burger which has, bacon, mushrooms, onions, arugula and a fried egg, NOT what I ordered. So it was taken back and the next burger had absolutely nothing on it. Instead of taking it back the items were brought to me so I could put it together.  Wasn't able to finish the burger since I ordered it well done and it was med to rare!! Since I don't like sea food and the burger is NOT the best burger in town anymore, I will not be back again. The 2 stars are for the lobster bisque that others at my table had and said it was really good. Disappointing birthday today!!< /Review>

<Text>My husband and I were visiting from out of town and our hotel had recommended Enterprise for dinner. The food was pretty good but we were very disappointed with our service. When we arrived we were sat at a high top table. Our waitress greeted us and took our drink order. She brought our drinks timely and then we didn't see her for quite some time... I was finally able to flag her down after about 20 minutes and I asked if she was our waitress (which she originally was) and she said no. I asked if she could send our waitress so we could order and she said, "I'd just prefer to put in the order in for you." She put in our appetizer order and another waitress brought it out for us. I asked if the new gal if she was our waitress now and she said no, but our waitress got busy with a 18 top table. Our original waitress never returned and every time we wanted to order another glass of wine or needed something - we had to just flag someone down. Needless to say, we won't be returning to Enterprise.< /Text>< userid>

< Rating>
4</Rating>
< Text>
My lobster bisque was creamy, nicely seasoned and delicious!  It lacked meaty chunks of lobster, but nonetheless it was a satisfying starter.  On the menu board they display the available daily fish offerings (from the Pacific to the Atlantic).  I wanted to go with something local so chose the Pacific Rock Fish - a white fish.  It tasted very fresh, and arrived on the plate with a diced mango salsa on top and a light butter/wine reduction sauce (not so buttery as to overpower the fish).  It was accompanied by tasty grilled yellow squash and zucchini (you choose from several sides).  This is a great place to take out-of-town guests.  It is sure to impress with the seafood kitschy decor and the large open grill area.  The lunch prices are reasonable and service was friendly.</Text>

< Text>
I have been eating at Enterprise in both Santa Monica and Santa Barbara for the past thirty years.   I was extremely disappointed in yesterday's meal.   Even now so as it has been a favorite.

The service was slow, not so much because of our easier, just understaffed for the number of customers.

I ordered the Salmon Greek Salad, and it was boring and flavorless.   Tiny pieces of feta but huge chunks of onions, peppers and tomatoes.   No black olives which I thought was odd.   If there was vinegar in the dressing, you couldn't taste it, nor did the oil have the flavor or constistancy of olive oil.   The salmon itself was overcooked, dry and flavorless.    It was very disappointing as I was looking forward to the quality I am used to.   There are plenty of other options at the same price level with higher quality.</Text>

< user_name>
Javier Ochoa< /user_name>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<rating>3<//rating><Review>This is a classic Santa Barbara spot, and I have been coming here since the mid 1970s. It's best for the happy hour, a few beers and some oysters, less so for dining. The happy hour is great- you get a great seat on State Street in an atmospheric old-school bar section, with a nice beer selection and some good seafood snacks. Back in the day, we would come here for fresh local fish, and the disappointment for lunch and dinner is that the menu is pretty much the same stuff you can get frozen at Trader Joe's: mahi mahi, salmon, scallops, shrimp (some decent medium prawns and the little tender pink cocktail ones), trout, dungeness crab, nothing you can't make just as well on your own or find at practically any seafood joint in the country. This makes me think that the business model is now geared away from fresh local seafood for locals and toward dependable dishes for the tourist market. I understand, but it's sad not to be able to eat great local fish at a SB institution anymore.<//Review><GmapID>0x80e913891aa55b8d:0xd8aecf460e2b2f33< /GmapID><date>1532915163820<//date><Resp>None<//Resp><Pics>None</Pics>< user_id>

0x80e913891aa55b8d:0xd8aecf460e2b2f33< /GmapID>
<Resp>None< /Resp>< review>
We have two kids and walked in with a stroller. . the two hostesses looked at each other like OMG...and we got put in the back all alone. Kids were dying to see fish tank and kitchen and I wanted to see the game on the TVs. No dice even tho there were plenty of tables open.

Food was very good but not amazing. All bread is sourdough for better or worse.

I would not come again even though this could have been a great place from the food and decor.

I had the mixed grill. 6 very nicely but small pieces of fish. Also lobster bisque is the bomb. Wife had mahi and let me taste it. Also excellent.

Kids meals came in a boat which was cool thought I would have probably preferred it come without pudding as my kids went straight for desert.</review>

<Name>Seth Weintraub</Name><date>1358565277783</date><rating>4</rating>< Text>
We have two kids and walked in with a stroller. . the two hostesses looked at each other like OMG...and we got put in the back all alone. Kids were dying to see fish tank and kitchen and I wanted to see the game on the TVs. No dice even tho there were plenty of tables open.

Food was very good but not amazing. All bread is sourdough for better or worse.

I would not come again even though this could have been a great place from the food and decor.

I had the mixed grill. 6 very nicely but small pieces of fish. Also lobster bisque is the bomb. Wife had mahi and let me taste it. Also excellent.

Kids meals came in a boat which was cool thought I would have probably preferred it come without pudding as my kids went straight for desert.<//Text>

<name>Darien Guy</name>< Date>
1504843444479< /Date>
<Rating>4< /Rating>< review>
We were in town for an anniversary weekend. We asked our hotel for an inexpensive seafood recommendation and he suggested Brophy Brothers. We stopped by and looked at the menu but we weren't impressed. We decided to walk up State street and see if anything caught our eye. This place had a menu that looked good and the prices weren't too bad.

This place seems to be very popular. It was pretty packed on a Thursday night. The wife had miso glazed sea bass and I had sesame crusted  Ahi. The wife had lobster bisque with her dinner and it was spectacular. Probably the best lobster bisque I've ever had.

The sea bass was quite good. Perfectly cooked and not too sweet. My Ahi was also good but I would have preferred a bit lighter on the sesame  crust.

All in all the experience was good. About the only negative was that the service was slow.</review>
